          "body": "The blessing of 48:15-16 is the chapter's theological summit and one of the most carefully constructed speeches in Genesis. It has three invocations in grammatical parallel: 'The God before whom my fathers Abraham and Isaac walked' (covenant continuity across three generations); 'The God who has been my shepherd all my life to this day' (personal providence, present tense); 'The Angel who has redeemed me from all evil' (specific deliverance, covenantal rescue). The three are invoked together as a single blessing agent — 'may He bless the lads.' The Angel of the third clause is placed in grammatical parity with God — a pattern the Old Testament sustains in the Angel-of-the-LORD appearances (Genesis 16:7-13; 32:24-30; Exodus 3:2-6). Jacob asks that the lads 'grow into a multitude in the midst of the earth' — the same fruitfulness-promise of 48:4 now targeted at the two boys personally. Spurgeon noted that Jacob, blind and dying, invoked more of the character of God in one breath than many healthy men in a sermon."
