        "body": "Before Jacob does anything in this chapter he recites. He tells Joseph about El Shaddai's appearance at Luz — the Bethel theophany of Genesis 28 and its renewal in Genesis 35 — and he quotes the three pillars of the covenant God confirmed there: fruitfulness, a company of peoples, and the everlasting land-grant. Only after establishing that prior word does he proceed to adopt Ephraim and Manasseh. The rhetorical structure is significant: Jacob does not bless on his own authority as patriarch; he blesses as the recipient and transmitter of a prior divine word. His authority in the chapter is derivative, not original.\n\nThe adoption declaration of 48:5 ('Ephraim and Manasseh shall be mine') is framed as an inference from the covenant. God promised fruitfulness and a company of peoples — Jacob's adoption of Joseph's sons is the mechanism by which Joseph participates in that company as two tribes rather than one. The legal background is the ancient Near Eastern custom by which a father could formally adopt and elevate a grandson, overriding the rights of biological birth order. Jacob does not break with legal convention in adopting the boys; he uses legal convention in service of a theological purpose.\n\nVerse 7's intrusion of Rachel's death is interpretively contested. Some commentators (Wenham, Word Biblical Commentary) read it as Jacob's explanation for the adoption — since Joseph is Rachel's firstborn, Jacob is compensating for what Rachel's line should have received. Others (Hamilton, NICOT) read it as personal context for why Ephraim and Manasseh are so precious to Jacob. What is certain is that the narrator preserves it without editorial comment, which is the narrator's way of honoring its emotional weight without resolving its ambiguity. The grief belongs. It has a home inside the covenant, even if it does not have a function in the argument.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *El Shaddai* (48:3) — God Almighty, the covenant name especially associated with the patriarchal promises (Genesis 17:1; 28:3; 35:11). *Achuzzat olam* (48:4) — 'everlasting possession': *achuzzah* is the legal term for a possession held by right, not merely by occupancy; *olam* is the perpetuity modifier used in covenant contexts throughout Genesis 17. *Sakhal* (48:14) — to act wisely, prudently; the same root as the Servant's prudence in Isaiah 52:13 — the narrator signals that what follows is prophetic wisdom, not geriatric confusion."
