        "excerpt": "Joseph said to his father, 'They are my sons, whom God has given me here.' So he said, 'Bring them to me, please, that I may bless them.'",
        "body": "The scene of approach in 48:8-12 is the chapter's most visually rich unit. Jacob, whose eyes are dim (48:10), asks 'Who are these?' — a question that echoes Isaac's dim-eyed failure to identify Jacob in Genesis 27:18. The parallel is deliberate and ironic: Isaac's dim eyes enabled a deception; Jacob's dim eyes introduce a scene of honest, intentional blessing. Physical sight fails both men; covenantal sight does not. Jacob cannot see Ephraim and Manasseh, but he knows exactly what he is doing when he blesses them.\n\nJoseph's answer — 'They are my sons, whom God has given me here' — is a confession of faith embedded in plain speech. 'Here' means Egypt, the land of exile. But even in Egypt, God has given sons. Even in Pharaoh's court, the covenant is active. Joseph's reflex is to attribute the gift to God, not to his own management of his life. This is the Joseph of Genesis 45:5-8 — the man who reads providence in everything and credits God with everything.\n\nJacob's embrace and kiss of the lads (48:10) is the only physical tenderness in the chapter, and it echoes Jacob's own reception by Esau after decades of separation (Genesis 33:4). Then Joseph removes the boys from Jacob's knees and bows with his face to the ground (48:12). The gesture of bowing (*shachah*) is worship posture — the same posture Joseph saw in his boyhood dream (Genesis 37:7-9). The brothers, his father, his mother — all would bow before him. Now the dream's recipient bows before his blind, dying father. Providence has moved in precisely the arc God ordained, and the man who read it best has the humility to acknowledge it with his body.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Palal* (48:11, translated 'expected') — the verb normally means 'to pray' or 'to judge'; here in the reflexive (hitpallel) it carries the sense of 'to think possible,' 'to hope for,' 'to count on.' Jacob is saying he never dared pray for or count on seeing Joseph's face again. *Shachah* (48:12, bowed with his face to the ground) — the standard term for prostration in worship. Joseph's posture before Jacob is simultaneously filial honor and covenantal acknowledgment."
