        "body": "The blessing of 48:15-16 is structured as a three-part divine invocation followed by a fourfold petition. The three invocations are in grammatical parallel, all governing the single verb 'bless' — they describe one agent acting under three aspects of His character and relationship to Jacob. First: 'The God before whom my fathers Abraham and Isaac walked' — the covenant God, historically specific, known across three named generations. Second: 'The God who has been my shepherd all my life to this day' — the same God experienced personally, providentially, and continuously. Third: 'The Angel who has redeemed me from all evil' — the delivering agent who fought Jacob at the Jabbok (Genesis 32:24-30), whom Hosea identifies as both 'the angel' and God Himself (Hosea 12:4-5).\n\nThe third invocation demands attention. Placing 'the Angel' in grammatical parity with 'God' as co-agent of the blessing is the most theologically suggestive move in the chapter. Jewish interpreters from the Targums onward were aware of the tension and variously identified the Angel as Michael, as the divine presence itself, or (in the Alexandrian tradition) as the Logos. Christian interpreters from Justin Martyr through Calvin read the Angel-of-the-LORD consistently as the pre-incarnate Son — the Second Person of the Trinity who appeared in theophanic form throughout the patriarchal period. Calvin comments: 'The angel who is here introduced is not a created angel, but He who was the mediator between God and men before he was manifested in the flesh' (Commentary on Genesis, 48:16). The text does not require the Trinitarian reading but is not resistant to it; what it clearly requires is that the Angel who redeems is invested with divine authority sufficient to bless.\n\nThe four petitions of the blessing are: (1) 'bless the lads,' (2) 'may my name live on in them, and the names of my fathers Abraham and Isaac,' (3) 'may they grow into a multitude in the midst of the earth.' The carrying of covenant names is the patriarchal equivalent of the New Covenant 'name above every name' — name-bearing is identity, inheritance, and belonging. To bear the names of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob is to be inside the covenant-line. Ephraim and Manasseh, Egyptian-born, are now inside that line in the most permanent way possible.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ro'eh* (shepherd, 48:15) — from the root *ra'ah*, to pasture, tend, shepherd. The word applied to God appears in Psalm 23:1 (*YHWH ro'i*) and Genesis 49:24 (*ro'eh even yisrael*, the Shepherd, the Stone of Israel). *Gaal* (redeemed, 48:16) — the go'el verb; this is the only use of *gaal* in Genesis; it becomes the redemption-word of Exodus (6:6; 15:13) and Isaiah (43:1; 44:22-23). *Maleakh* (angel, 48:16) — messenger, divine representative; the grammatical parity with *Elohim* in the same invocation is the chapter's theological pressure-point."
