        "body": "The chapter closes with Jacob addressing Joseph alone after the blessing of the lads has been sealed. The movement from blessing (48:15-20) to prophetic promise (48:21-22) mirrors the structure of chapter 49 — Jacob moves from enacted blessing to verbal declaration. Two promises conclude the chapter. First: 'God will be with you, and bring you back to the land of your fathers' (48:21). Jacob does not promise his own return; he knows he is dying in Egypt. He promises Joseph's return — and by 'you' he almost certainly means the extended family, the nation forming in Goshen. This promise reaches across the four centuries of Egyptian slavery to the Exodus. It is the same promise Joseph will echo on his own deathbed: 'God will surely take care of you, and you shall carry my bones up from here' (Genesis 50:24-25).\n\nThe second promise — 'I give you one portion more than your brothers, which I took from the hand of the Amorite with my sword and my bow' (48:22) — is exegetically contested. The Hebrew word is *shekhem*, which can mean 'shoulder' or 'ridge' (a toponym for Shechem), and the reference to conquest 'with my sword and my bow' does not correspond to any recorded military action by Jacob. Several interpretive options exist: (1) Jacob speaks of a future conquest by his descendants (prophetic perfect); (2) he refers to the events of Genesis 34 in language that assigns corporate responsibility to himself rather than Simeon and Levi; (3) he refers to a now-lost tradition of Jacob's own fighting. The Samaritan Targum and some rabbinic traditions favor option 2. What is uncontested is that Shechem becomes Joseph's special inheritance: Joshua 24:32 records the burial of Joseph's bones at Shechem 'on the piece of ground which Jacob had bought from the sons of Hamor the father of Shechem for one hundred pieces of money.'\n\nThe writer of Hebrews sees the whole chapter through the lens of faith: 'By faith Jacob, as he was dying, blessed each of the sons of Joseph, and worshiped, leaning on the top of his staff' (Hebrews 11:21). The staff is the pilgrim's staff — Jacob has been a sojourner his whole life (Genesis 47:9), and he dies as a sojourner, worshiping the God of the promise with his body supported by the traveler's stick. Faith here is not optimism about circumstances (Jacob dies in Egypt, not Canaan) but confident orientation toward a promise whose fulfillment lies entirely in God's hands. Tim Keller notes that this is the pattern of biblical faith throughout: it is most clearly itself when it believes most specifically against the most evident impossibility."
